related_items.title: The long arm of justice : lessons from specialized war crimes units in France, Germany, and the Netherlands /
description: "This 109-page report examines the inner workings of war crimes units in the three countries and highlights key lessons learned. Since justice is often elusive where the crimes occurred, national courts in these three states and elsewhere are more frequently applying the longstanding principle of "universal jurisdiction" to prosecute suspects accused of genocide, crimes against humanity, war crimes, and torture, regardless of where the crimes were committed and the victim's and accused's nationality."--Publisher's website.
other_title: Lessons from specialized war crimes units in France, Germany, and the Netherlands

related_items.title: Hermann Göring at public events and other activities, September-November 1940
description: 1 album (230 photographic prints) ; 43 x 37 cm. (album) | Photographs show Göring at command post of the Air Fleet 2 (Luftflotte 2) on the English Channel; awarding Iron Crosses to Werner Mölders, Adolf Galland and members of the I/KG 26 bomber command in Wevelgem, Belgium, members of the II/KG 53 bomber command in Tournei, France and members of the I/KG 76 and II/KG 76 bomber commands. Includes views of inspection tour of Air-Sea Rescue Service (Seenotdienst), Cherbourg, and of visit to Dunkirk, France. Includes views of meeting with Russian Foreign Minister V.M. Molotov and opening of exhibition "Der Sieg im Westen" (Victory in the West) in Vienna, Austria. Also includes views of the Göring family outdoors in the snow and formal portraits of the Göring family members by Rosemarie Clausen.

related_items.title: German and European money and scrip used during and after the first World war, 1914-1924
description: 19 albums (ca. 20,000 items) ; 31 x 42 cm. (album) | 1 folder (178 items) ; 24 x 30 cm. | Extensive collection of all kinds of German money and scrip "Notgeld", "Lagergeld", "Gutscheine" and "Serienscheine", chiefly the currency used during and after the first World war, 1914-1924, issued by principalities, German colonial governments, cities, large corporations, small businesses, prisoner-of-war camps, and in some cases, individuals. Some Austrian and French money, IOU's and scrip and examples from other European countries. One album is devoted to the huge denominations issued during the ruinous inflation, 1919-1923.
